column1: Who will win the election for California's 27th Congressional District in 2022?
column5: ['The Democratic Party candidate', 'The Republican Party candidate', 'Someone else']

column6: Garcia has won in much tougher national environments than this

A late break for R here in the prediction markets, poll aggregators, and forecasters. At the time of this forecast, only Cook Political Report and the crowd at Good Judgment Open were still calling this a relative toss-up.

Garcia (R) is 2-0 vs Smith (D) in a district rated D+4 by Cook. Their last election was extremely close and polls are inconsistent, but Pelosi's House Majority PAC recently turned off the funding faucet in this district. I doubt it's because they think they have the election wrapped up. The expert consensus gives Garcia roughly a 55-60% chance of winning. In light of the funding news, I'm bumping this one to 65-35, Garcia.
NYT: Democrats pulling ad buys because they see the district as increasingly out of reach
Abortion ruling has put these 5 California House races in play - Politico (Sep 18), https://www.politico.com/news/2022/09/18/california-abortion-house-roe-00057023
As complete a tossup as you're likely to find.
Strangely enough.... the base rate from 538 shows Dems slightly behind...

With redistricting its a complete game changer for the district otherwise known as the 27th. The 27th district now overlaps a healthy portion of real MAGA territory in the Antelope Valley so its unlike much of the rest of Southern California.
Urban constituency and nearly a decade of incumbent. Longstanding blue voting record of president and governor as well.

I wish I could take my last forecast back. It is a correct forecast for the pre-redistricting 27th district. Judy Chu won the 2020 election with nearly 80 percent of the vote. She, however, has been redistricted into another safe Democratic seat.

Said last time, this is one that could go either way and that was what happened, with Mike Garcia eventually beating Smith's lead. This time around it could be a safer bet for the Republicans, but still a close call.... and again might not be an overnight result

Mike Garcia has defended a seat twice when it was leaning +5 Dem, now it leans +8 D with redistricting. In the mean time the national environment has shifted +9 GOP, so he should be safe, but he was already running way ahead of what the GOP normally seems to do in this geographic region
